Architecture plan

Product/source of truth
- Product naming must come only from issue text and PRODUCT.md. PRODUCT.md is not present in the repository at setup time, so implementation should avoid introducing a product/brand name until that file or a future issue provides one.
- Current tracked repository content is minimal: README.md only. Issues specify a React frontend and Express backend.

Repository/module structure
- Root
  - package.json: workspace scripts for install, lint, typecheck, test, dev, build.
  - .env.example: documented DB, storage, Google OAuth, JWT, frontend/backend URL settings.
  - frontend/: React + TypeScript app.
    - src/app/: routing, top-level layout, auth provider wiring.
    - src/api/: typed API client, request helpers, auth token attachment, error normalization.
    - src/auth/: AuthContext, login callback handling, session persistence.
    - src/components/: shared UI primitives plus domain components such as PostCard, FollowButton, LikeButton, CommentList.
    - src/pages/: feed, profile, upload, auth callback.
    - src/types/: frontend-facing DTOs imported from or aligned with shared contracts.
    - src/test/: component test setup and utilities.
  - backend/: Express + TypeScript API.
    - src/server.ts: process entrypoint and listener.
    - src/app.ts: Express app assembly, middleware, routes, error handler.
    - src/config/: environment parsing and validation.
    - src/db/: Prisma client singleton and database utilities.
    - src/storage/: S3-compatible object storage client, upload helper, public/signed URL handling.
    - src/auth/: Google OAuth flow, JWT issue/verify helpers, auth middleware.
    - src/modules/users/: user service, routes, DTO mapping.
    - src/modules/posts/: upload/create/list post services and routes.
    - src/modules/follows/: follow/unfollow/count services and routes.
    - src/modules/likes/: like/unlike/count services and routes.
    - src/modules/comments/: create/list/delete comment services and routes.
    - src/modules/feed/: paginated feed aggregation service and routes.
    - src/middleware/: request logging, auth, validation, error handling.
    - src/types/: request user augmentation and shared backend types.
    - tests/: service/unit tests.
  - backend/prisma/
    - schema.prisma: User, Post, Follow, Like, Comment models.
    - migrations/: Prisma migrations created issue by issue.
  - shared/ or packages/shared/: shared API DTOs and validation schemas if the first implementation issue sets up workspaces. Otherwise keep DTOs duplicated narrowly until a shared package is justified.

Data model outline
- User: id, googleId unique, email unique, name, avatarUrl, createdAt, updatedAt.
- Post: id, authorId, imageUrl, caption optional, createdAt, updatedAt; indexed by authorId and createdAt.
- Follow: followerId, followeeId, createdAt; composite unique followerId+followeeId; prevent self-follow in service logic.
- Like: userId, postId, createdAt; composite unique userId+postId.
- Comment: id, postId, authorId, content, createdAt, updatedAt.

API shape
- Auth: GET /auth/google/start, GET /auth/google/callback, GET /me.
- Upload/posts: POST /uploads/images, POST /posts, GET /posts/:id, GET /users/:id/posts.
- Follows: POST /users/:id/follow, DELETE /users/:id/follow, GET /users/:id/follow-counts.
- Feed: GET /feed?cursor=&limit=.
- Likes: POST /posts/:id/like, DELETE /posts/:id/like, GET /posts/:id/likes.
- Comments: GET /posts/:id/comments, POST /posts/:id/comments, DELETE /comments/:id.
- Responses should use consistent JSON envelopes and central error mapping by Issue #31.

Issue dependency plan
- Foundation: #1 creates frontend/backend structure; #2 adds TypeScript, ESLint, Prettier; #5 adds env contract; #3 adds Prisma/PostgreSQL; #4 adds object storage.
- Auth/user base: #6 depends on Prisma; #7 depends on users/env; #8 depends on OAuth; #9 creates frontend auth client; #10 and #11 consume frontend auth.
- Posting: #12 defines posts; #13 uploads images using storage and auth; #14 creates posts; #15 builds upload UI; #16 renders post cards.
- Follows/feed: #17 defines follows; #18 exposes follow APIs; #19 adds follow UI; #20 builds feed from current user plus followees; #21 builds feed UI.
- Likes: #22 defines likes; #23 exposes like APIs and counts; #24 adds frontend like controls.
- Comments: #25 defines comments; #26 exposes comment APIs; #27 adds frontend comment UI.
- Quality/release: #28 backend unit tests after services exist; #29 frontend component tests after key UI exists; #30 E2E after full workflow exists; #31 final error handling and self-host deployment review.

Key design decisions
- Keep backend business rules in services and route handlers thin. This makes #28 service tests practical and prevents duplicated rules across endpoints.
- Use Prisma composite unique constraints for Follow and Like idempotency, with services translating constraint failures into stable API responses.
- Use cursor pagination for feed/posts/comments where chronological ordering matters. Use createdAt plus id as a stable cursor to avoid skipped/duplicated rows.
- Store uploaded image metadata as URLs on Post; keep binary storage in object storage only.
- Keep JWT in frontend-managed session storage/local storage only if required by the initial auth implementation; prefer a single API client abstraction so storage choice can change later without touching components.
- Centralize env validation early so later issues fail fast in local and self-hosted deployments.
- Normalize API errors in backend and frontend. Backend returns structured codes/messages; frontend API client maps them to component-friendly errors.
- Prefer integration between shared DTO/validation schemas and API client once workspaces exist. If workspace setup is delayed, keep explicit TypeScript interfaces near the API client and reconcile with backend route DTOs during test issues.
